node.text:
Thanks to our fantastic sponsor: @matific I am sharing essential tips for teachers to prepare for the school year! Feel free to share or ask questions and add your own tips in the comments section. For more tips, be sure to check out my new blog post in which I share additional information and ideas that will help us all start the year calm and ready to go! ~ Jen
.

❤️Jen @living_future_memories @where_heart_meets_home

Flower name/words 💜💚 Did you know that the seasons DO NOT change on the same date in all the countries around the world?! I learned something new this week. In Australia our seasons are based on the months of the year: Summer starts 1st December, Autumn (not Fall here😉) starts 1st March, Winter starts 1st June, Spring 1st September. This doesn’t include the Northern Territory in Australia which has different seasons. In the US the seasons start on different days!! I never knew this! What are the arrangement of the seasons where you live? Tell us! Jen x ❤️ @living_future_memories 🏡 @where_heart_meets_home 🏫 @invite_to_learn @st_petersanglican 

{Activity shown is great for early literacy used with letters, words, or for numeracy with numbers, and great for fine motor development. Questions and shares welcome.😊}

Silicone oven mit + watercolour art 🌈 It can’t get more simple than this! It’s a perfect example of following my class. Here I’ve mixed their love of art with their obsession with colour mixing, all while working on their fine motor skills.👌🙌 {Obviously earlier in the year before the current situation in Sydney Australia. 10weeks+ at home now.} 
.
.
How to:
1️⃣Mix small amounts of liquid watercolour or food colouring with water in jars.
2️⃣Place ice cube tray and/or oven mit on towelling (or a towel).
3️⃣Add droppers and allow child to experiment.
.
.
This activity was such a winner it is sure to bring smiles to little faces.😊 Libby had a go last week at home. Will you give this a go?!! ~ Jen x

❤️Jen {The teacher now in lockdown 10 weeks & counting, working full time mostly remotely (really more than one job right now- teaching + check out my work on @st_petersanglican & @invite_to_learn 😅) with 5 of my own kids currently remote learning + one onsite for a traineeship + shift working hubby. It’s a bit (a lot) crazy, which is why I’ve been away from this account, but I love my life! If you want to see what it looks like for my family of 8 in lockdown head on over to @living_future_memories ❤️ I post in stories & have created highlights. I’m using that account to focus on the good in our current challenging situation. Thanks for the kind messages! 😘}

node.text:
Just think, a term ago I was excitedly showing you all my classroom! For those of you interested in a possible new enrolment in early learning at this lovely school @st_petersanglican there is an information session on at 1:30 tomorrow (Thursday). Register on the website for the virtual event. The link is also in stories on @invite_to_learn 😘

Now, about my class: I miss them terribly but am very thankful for Zoom. We are currently focusing on questions and sharing our wonderings. The parents of my students are incredible and are doing amazing things at home. I keep telling myself it’s not forever. If you have any advice, fun Zoom ideas, great online resources, I’m always open to reading more. I am not perfect, and am as much a learner as anyone, including my students.💕 Jen @living_future_memories

Butterfly love🦋 Easy, fun & inexpensive are always a winner! I especially love when a fun art process becomes not only a beautiful product but is also something that can be used later in play. This is a great example!

1️⃣Colour paper towel with washable markers.
2️⃣Spray with water and leave to dry.
3️⃣Gather middle of the paper towel and clip with a peg to make a butterfly.

This could be a great provocation with older grades to discuss symmetry, or for younger grades patterns, or environments in which animals live, adaptation, change etc. It can be a stand alone activity, sure, but I love it when things like this can lead into discussion & further learning/questioning/curiosity. This was first posted on @invite_to_learn ~Jen x @living_future_memories @where_heart_meets_home

Have I ever inspired you? Perhaps to try something new, make small changes, or big ones! Please, please comment to let me know. Today I could really use the encouragement. We all need it from time to time. If you like what you see on someone else’s post, maybe write something today.❤️ In return I’ve posted some favourites for you.😘😘

1️⃣Changing the shelf invites interest. We are wired to be curious about change/novelty.
2️⃣Lego/duplo geoboard.
3️⃣Nature paint brushes. Use paper tape to attach.
4️⃣Frozen paint on pop sticks. Paper in a tray is really helpful here.
5️⃣The go-to dining room shelf.
6️⃣Masking/paper/painters tape with markers- helps to learn about writing on lines.
7️⃣Number bead threading on pipe cleaners (number beans!)
8️⃣Rock and magnet patterns on a chalk board.
9️⃣Letters and numbers on leaves. Very inexpensive resource!
🔟Catalogue cutting! Children love choosing things to cut and glue.

Tuff tray love❤️ I’m constantly asked where I purchased my black tray or the school tuff tray. Both places no longer stock them. BUT I noticed that @thecreativetoyshop DO sell them now, which is awesome. I’m just about to place an order for Libby’s birthday (it’s Wednesday, so I’m pushing it I know🙈😬) and it made me think to share this. I’ve added a few of my fav tuff tray ideas, both for those who are cool with the mess and those who aren’t into it. All of these ideas were really popular, and I hope it helps a few of you.😘 

The upside down bath mat (from @kmartaus - very inexpensive) is awesome. Using it with a dropper and jars of coloured water is also great. Put some paper underneath and an art work is created at the same time.😊

For all of you who have reached out during this time of lockdown for my family and I - thank you!! I’m not going to pretend working full time (1 day onsite, 4 from home- really 6 days as one of the parents from school said in an email to me❤️) with 5 of my children involved in remote learning, and a Hubby who works shift work at a hospital, is easy. It’s not. But I’m looking for the good in every day, am soaking up every opportunity to connect with students at school (I miss them all so much😢), and have organised well with a good rhythm at home, so it is working for now. I just have very little down time or sleep.😂 All the children in my care are worth every single second & I hope I can be someone who makes this time a little bit better. It’s in the dark times we need to be the light.✨

Now, where are you on the messy play continuum??! All-the-mess-all-the-time, mess-within-reason, occasionally-messy, once-in-awhile-messy, easy-clean-up-only, never-messy-play. There is nothing wrong with any of these! Families enjoying their time together is best.❤️ Jen @living_future_memories
